Premier League Dynamics (2019-2023): Manchester City Dominance, Arsenal Rise, Notable Trends.

Authors: Taahaa Dawe, Dhruv Gupta, Ghizlane Rehioui

Introduction

EPL (English Premier Leagure) is the most watched soccer league in the world. The Premier League is the top level of English football. There are 20 teams in the league, and they move up or down in the league system. They play against each other twice, once at their home stadium and once at the other team's stadium. The season usually goes from August to May, and each team plays 38 matches. The competition was founded as the FA Premier League on 20 February 1992 following the decision of First Division (top-tier league from 1888 until 1992) clubs to break away from the English Football League. The main reason of choosing EPL data was due to the easy availability of data throughout the years. Being the most popular league in the world, it's easy to find updated data for all the participating teams.

Problem Statement

Objectives:

The research starts with answering the question 'What are the average goals scored per season for the Top 5 EPL teams, and how do those teams rank against each other?'

More generally, this research aims to assess the performance of the Top 5 teams (based on the total goals scored) over the five seasons 2019-2023 while making sure that the performance metrics are varied. Additionally, some hypothesis about Arsenal are tested.

Research Questions:

  • RQ1: Does the observed sample mean of 1.71 for the average goals scored by Arsenal, derived from a dataset, provide statistically significant evidence to reject the claim made on the Manchester Citys Official Website (Cox, 2023) that the average number of goals scored by Arsenal is 2.31?

    • $H_0: \mu = 2.31$,
    • $H_a: \mu \neq 2.31$,

  • RQ2: Is there compelling evidence in the dataset to support the claim that there has been a substantial increase in possession for Arsenal in 2022 compared to 2019?

    • $H_0: _D = 0$
    • $H_a: _D> 0$

Data

The data utilized for this analysis was scraped from the FBRef website, a reputable source for football statistics and history. The focus of this project was on gathering and analyzing individual team match data from the Premier League, spanning from the 2019 season to the current season, 2023. In addition to the points table information, we also retrieved crucial shooting statistics for each team in every match from the shooting table. This comprehensive dataset allows for a detailed exploration of team performance metrics and shooting proficiency within the Premier League during the specified timeframe.

NOTE: The following section contains the scraping code as a markdown because scraping takes more than one hour.

team_data.head()

#Scraping data for multiple seasons and teams with a loop
from datetime import datetime

current_year = datetime.now().year
years = list(range(current_year, 2016, -1))
all_matches = []

years #The year'2016' is actually the season '2015-2016'. We use this everywhere which makes working with the data easier.

standings_url = "https://fbref.com/en/comps/9/Premier-League-Stats"

for year in years:

    data = requests.get(standings_url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(data.text)
    standings_table = soup.select('table.stats_table')[0]

    links = [l.get("href") for l in standings_table.find_all('a')]
    links = [l for l in links if '/squads/' in l]

    team_urls = [f"https://fbref.com{l}" for l in links]

    previous_season = soup.select("a.prev")[0].get("href")
    standings_url = f"https://fbref.com{previous_season}"

for team_url in team_urls:

    team_name = team_url.split("/")[-1].replace("-Stats", "").replace("-", " ")
    data = requests.get(team_url)
    matches = pd.read_html(data.text, match="Scores & Fixtures")[0]
    soup = BeautifulSoup(data.text)

    links = [l.get("href") for l in soup.find_all('a')]
    links = [l for l in links if l and 'all_comps/shooting/' in l]

    data = requests.get(f"https://fbref.com{links[0]}")
    
    shooting = pd.read_html(data.text, match="Shooting")[0]
    shooting.columns = shooting.columns.droplevel()

    try:
        team_data = matches.merge(shooting[["Date", "Sh", "SoT", "Dist", "FK", "PK", "PKatt"]], on="Date")
    except ValueError:
        continue

    team_data = team_data[team_data["Comp"] == "Premier League"]
    team_data["Season"] = year
    team_data["Team"] = team_name
    all_matches.append(team_data)
    time.sleep(1)

len(all_matches)
match_df = pd.concat(all_matches) # Combining the individual dataframes into a single dataframe

#Data cleaning before converting to csv
match_df.columns = [c.lower() for c in match_df.columns]

The scraped data considers only Premier League for the seasons between 2019 and 2023 and is composed of 3138 rows and 26 columns. The next section will deal with the pre-processing of the dataset.

Column Description

The scraped data consists of 26 columns:

  • 'Unnamed: 0': Row number of data
  • 'date': Date of the match
  • 'time': Time of match
  • 'comp': Competition name
  • 'round': Matchweek number
  • 'day': Day of the week
  • 'venue': Where the game is played (Away or Home)
  • 'result': W for Win, D for Draw, and L for Loss
  • 'goals_scored': Number of goals scored
  • 'goals_conceded': Number of goals conceded
  • 'opponent': Opponent team name
  • 'expected_goals': Expected goals to score
  • 'expected_assists': Expected assists provided
  • 'possession': Duration for which the team had the ball possession
  • 'attendance': Count of audience
  • 'captain': Captain of team
  • 'formation': Team formation
  • 'referee': Referee name
  • 'shots': Shots taken by team
  • 'shots_on_target': Shots on target by team
  • 'avg_shot_distance': Average shot distance
  • 'freekicks': Freekicks taken
  • 'penaltykicks': Penalties taken
  • 'penaltykicks_opponent': Penalties given to opponent
  • 'season': Season year
  • 'team': Team

Distribution & Correlation Comparison

  • The features of possession and shots are positively correlated as depicted in the Pair Plot. This is also confirmed by the Correlation Matrix above, correlating 0.55. This makes sense because the more a team has the ball, the more chances they have at scoring. The same is found for shots_on_target with shots (0.69), goals_scored with shots_on_target (0.59), and possession with shots_on_target (0.35). Some smaller positive correlations are found for possession with goals_scored (0.18).

  • The possession with goals_conceded, shots_on_target with goals_conceded, goals_conceded with goals_scored, and goals_conceded with shots are negatively correlated but not strongly, with values between -0.19 and -0.15. The rest of the correlations between the remaining variables are negligible.

  • Based on the Pair Plot, the distributions of each variable of interest is the same regardless of the season and for all teams. The features shots, shots_on_target, and possession appear to have a distribution that are close to the normal distribution with median values of 10 shots, 2.5 shots on target, and 50 minutes respectively for every season. The features shots and shots_on_target have slightly skewed curves in the same direction.

  • Only the year 2023 looks different and much lower than the other seasons. The goals_scored and goals_conceded appear to be about the same shape. This is because the season 2023 is not yet finished and the data for it is not yet available.

Identifying Overperforming Football Teams Based on Goals Scored and Expected Goals (xG)

In the realm of football analytics, Expected Goals (xG) has emerged as a pivotal metric for evaluating team performance. xG quantifies the likelihood of a shot resulting in a goal, taking into account numerous factors like shot location, type, and defensive pressure. Assessing how a team performs relative to their xG provides crucial insights into their offensive efficiency.

Objective

This analysis seeks to identify overperforming football teams by contrasting their Goals Scored with Expected Goals (xG). Overperforming teams consistently score more goals than their xG projections suggest. The analysis is divided into two main parts:

Part 1: Identifying Top 5 Overperforming Teams Each Year

In this segment, we dissect individual football seasons to pinpoint teams that have excelled in surpassing their xG projections. The process involves calculating Goals Scored and xG for each team within a season and identifying the top 5 teams with the highest positive differences between Goals Scored and xG.

In[]:
df2 = df[df['team'].isin(top)]

df2['goals_over_xG'] = df2['goals_scored'] - df2['expected_goals']

# Group data by year (season) and team, and calculate the total goals over xG
grouped = df2.groupby(['season', 'team'])['goals_over_xG'].sum().reset_index()

# Sort the data by season and goals over xG in descending order
sorted_data = grouped.sort_values(by=['season', 'goals_over_xG'], ascending=[True, False])

# Get the top 5 overperforming teams for each year
top_teams = sorted_data.groupby('season').head(5)

# Create visualizations for each year
for year, group in top_teams.groupby('season'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.barh(group['team'], group['goals_over_xG'], color='skyblue')
    plt.xlabel('Goals Over xG')
    plt.ylabel('Team')

Using Percentage Terms for Overperformance Analysis

In our ongoing analysis, we have made a significant adjustment in the way we assess teams' overperformance relative to Expected Goals (xG). Rather than relying solely on total overperformance values, we have transitioned to using percentage terms. This shift offers a more meaningful and equitable basis for comparison across seasons and teams. Here's why percentage terms are a better choice for comparison:

1. Standardized Assessment: Total overperformance values may be influenced by the volume of scoring opportunities a team encounters in a given season. Teams with more opportunities are likely to have higher total overperformance figures. By calculating percentage overperformance, we standardize the assessment, enabling fair comparisons irrespective of variations in opportunities.

2. Reflecting Efficiency: Percentage overperformance provides insights into a team's efficiency in front of the goal. It gauges a team's ability to make the most of the opportunities they create, which is a key indicator of offensive prowess.

3. Comparative Analysis: Using percentage terms allows us to evaluate teams on a level playing field, making it easier to identify consistent overperformers across different seasons. This approach helps us pinpoint teams that consistently excel in converting opportunities into goals, regardless of the total number of chances.

Now, let's proceed to examine the results of our analysis using percentage terms for overperformance:

Hypothesis Testing

Manchester City Official's Website claims that the average number of goals scored by Arsenal is 2.31. Based on the current dataset, the average goals scored by Arsenal is:

In[]:
df[(df["team"] == "Arsenal")]["goals_scored"].mean()
Out[]:
1.713375796178344

with sample size

In[]:
df[(df["team"] == "Arsenal")]["goals_scored"].count()
Out[]:
157

It may seem like a big difference. But could it have been by chance? Can we conclude that the average goals scored by arsenal in our sample is not equal to population?

Hypothesis Test 1:

To answer the previous question, a one-sample test will be performed in the following setup:

  • $H_0: \mu = 2.31$,

  • $H_1 : \mu \neq 2.31$,

where the sample mean $\bar{X}$ is the test statistic and $\bar{x} = 1.71$, $n=157$.

If the true mean is really 2.31, what is the probability of getting values of $\bar{X}$ at least as contradictory to = 2.31 as $\bar{x}$ = 1.71, for a random sample of the same size and variance? So at least as contradictory is at least as far away from 2.31 as 1.71.

In[]:
arsenal_goals_scored =df[(df["team"] == "Arsenal") ]["goals_scored"]
from scipy import stats
answer= stats.ttest_1samp(a = arsenal_goals_scored, popmean = 2.31)

if answer[1] < 0.05:
  print("Reject the null hypothesis")
else:
  print("Hypothesis can not be rejected")
print("The P-value is "+ str(answer[1]) )
print("The  test statistics "+str(answer[0]))
answer

Reject the null hypothesis
The P-value is 9.485911045404651e-08
The  test statistics -5.599006952234918
Out[]:
TtestResult(statistic=-5.599006952234918, pvalue=9.485911045404651e-08, df=156)
In[]:
import numpy as np
In[]:
import scipy.stats as st
import numpy as np

confidence_level = 0.95
degreef = len(arsenal_goals_scored) - 1
mean_goals_scored = np.mean(arsenal_goals_scored)
standard_error = st.sem(arsenal_goals_scored)

# Use confidence level instead of alpha
interval = st.t.interval(confidence_level, df=degreef, loc=mean_goals_scored, scale=standard_error)

print("Confidence Interval:", interval)

Confidence Interval: (1.5028912680019217, 1.9238603243547663)
  • The p-value is very small (less than $\alpha = 0.05$) which means we reject the Null Hypothesis. This means that there is a significant difference between the sample mean and the hypothesized population mean.

The statistical analysis conducted on the dataset for the average number of goals scored by Arsenal yielded the following results:

  1. P-value: $(9.49 \times 10^{-8})$ - This extremely small p-value provides strong evidence against the null hypothesis $(H_0: \mu = 2.31)$, suggesting that the average number of goals scored by Arsenal is significantly different from 2.31.

  2. Test Statistic: $(-5.60)$ - The negative test statistic indicates a deviation from the hypothesized mean, and its magnitude underscores the strength of the evidence against the null hypothesis.

  3. Confidence Interval: $(1.50, 1.92)$ - The confidence interval doesn't include the hypothesized mean of 2.31, providing further support for rejecting the null hypothesis.

In conclusion, based on the low p-value, the negative test statistic, and the confidence interval, there is robust evidence to reject the null hypothesis. This implies that the average number of goals scored by Arsenal, according to the dataset, differs significantly from the claimed value of 2.31.

Hypothesis Test 2:

$ \text{We have a dataset examining possession differences in 2022 vs 2019 for Arsenal.} \\ \text{We are interested in finding strong evidence that there this significtent increase in the possession in year 2022 i.e} \quad _d > 0 \\ \text{so the null hypothesis is that there is no significetent difference i.e} \quad _D = 0 $

$H_O : _D = 0 $

$ H_A: _D> 0 $
